    "discriminators": [
     "WINGS is the rare UCS category defined by a MORPHOLOGY rather than a source, and it is a good one: flapping is a PERIODIC ONSET TRAIN. onset_periodicity is genuinely diagnostic (a flap train is periodic where a rustle or an applause burst is stochastic), and onset_rate_per_second lands in the ~3-20/s band for a bird - fast enough to be clearly rhythmic, slow enough that the individual flaps remain resolvable as separate broadband thumps rather than fusing into a pitch. That is real, so signal_narrowable.",
     "Each flap is an unvoiced broadband air/feather thump: low harmonicity, high spectral_flatness. If the file has a tonal fundamental, it is not a bird wing.",
     "Against WINGS-INSECT: an insect beats its wings so fast (100-600 Hz) that the onset train FUSES INTO A TONE - the wingbeat rate becomes the audible pitch. Resolvable individual flaps means bird; a steady buzz whose pitch IS the flap rate means insect. That is a clean, physical, DSP-decidable boundary.",
     "Against WINGS-CREATURE: only implied body size (a dragon's flap is slower and lower). That part is text.",
     "A single takeoff burst rather than a flap train reads as one broadband impulse and can be lost to CLOTH or AIR movement."
    ],
