    "discriminators": [
     "The physical fact that makes this one measurable: an insect beats its wings roughly 100-600 times a second, far above the ear's flutter-fusion limit, so the onset train STOPS being rhythmic and BECOMES A TONE. A bee's wingbeat IS its pitch (~200 Hz); a mosquito's is ~600 Hz. So this subcategory is sustained_tonal with a harmonic-rich buzz, LOW onset_periodicity (there are no resolvable onsets left to be periodic), and high sustain and stationarity - the exact inverse of WINGS-BIRD's resolvable flap train. That boundary is genuine physics and needs no text: signal_narrowable.",
     "A Doppler-ish pitch and amplitude wobble as the insect passes the mic is characteristic; expect moderate spectral_flux on an otherwise stationary tone.",
     "It does NOT tell a bee from a wasp from a fly - the pitch differences are real but the ranges overlap, and recording distance changes the level, not the frequency. Species is text.",
     "The explanation admits overlap with ANIMALS-INSECT, and that overlap is total for a buzzing bee: the same file, filed by editorial intent. Do not expect DSP to split WINGS-INSECT from ANIMALS-INSECT.",
     "Confusable with a small motor, a fan or a MOTORS drone, all of which are also periodic-blade tones - a genuine failure mode of this signature."
    ],
